news|title=Liverpool 1\u20130 Reading|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19939536|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 October 2012|accessdate=24 August 2019}}<br>{{cite news|title=Reading 3\u20133 Fulham|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20014386|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 October 2012|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref> Three days later, on 30 October 2012, he scored his second goal for the club, in the League Cup campaign, as Reading lost 7\u20135 against Arsenal after Arsenal were 4\u20130 down before coming back to win the game 7\u20135 after extra-time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Ben|title=Reading 5\u20137 Arsenal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20053678|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 August 2012|date=30 October 2012}}</ref> After being sidelined in early\u20132013 due to injury, Leigterwood then captained the side for the first time and scored his third goal of the season, in a 4\u20130 win over [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in the third round of the FA Cup.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jason Roberts ruled out of West Brom clash|url=https://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/jason-roberts-ruled-out-west-4048564|publisher=Get Reading|date=11 January 2013|accessdate=24 August 2019}}<br>{{cite news|title=A right Royal thrashing: Hunt bags a brace as Reading run riot against Sheffield United|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/reading-4-0-sheffield-united-match-1557771|publisher=Daily Mirror|date=26 January 2013|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref> He continued to be in the starting line-up until he was dropped from the first team for the rest of the 2012\u201313 season, as Leigterwood went on to make thirty\u2013four appearances and scoring three times in all competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2013/march/why-ledge-stood-out/|title=Why Ledge stood out|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=16 March 2013|accessdate=24 August 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824134030/https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2013/march/why-ledge-stood-out/|archivedate=24 August 2019|url-status=live}}<br>{{cite web|url=https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2013/march/united-the-stats/|title=United: The Stats|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=19 March 2013|accessdate=24 August 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824134027/https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2013/march/united-the-stats/|archivedate=24 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] named Leigterwood as the Premier League's worst XI of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Football's flops: The Premier League's worst XI of the season|url=https://metro.co.uk/2013/05/02/footballs-flops-the-premier-leagues-worst-xi-this-season-3710871/|publisher=Metro|date=2 May 2013|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the 2013\u201314 season, Leigterwood suffered an ankle injury during the pre\u2013season, having been on a knife since May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2013/july/leigertwood-injury/|title=Leigertwood injury|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=15 July 2013|accessdate=24 August 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824133856/https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2013/july/leigertwood-injury/|archivedate=24 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2013, he returned to training after recovering from the ankle injury.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mikele Leigertwood edges closer to a return for Reading FC|url=https://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/mikele-leigertwood-edges-closer-return-5940934|publisher=Get Reading|date=13 September 2013|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref> Upon returning to training from injury, Leigterwood's return was praised by Manager [[Nigel Adkins]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2013/october/the-ultimate-professional-/|title='The ultimate professional'|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=6 October 2013|accessdate=24 August 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824133908/https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2013/october/the-ultimate-professional-/|archivedate=24 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, his return was short\u2013lived and his injury plagued was plagued throughout 2013 and early 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2013/october/injury-latest/|title=Injury Latest|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=24 October 2013|accessdate=24 August 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824134023/https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2013/october/injury-latest/|archivedate=24 August 2019|url-status=live}}<br>{{cite news|title=Royals opt against operation on injured skipper Morrison|url=https://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/reading-fc-opt-against-operation-6336404|publisher=Get Reading|date=24 November 2013|accessdate=24 August 2019}}<br>{{cite news|title=Charles Watts' Big Match Preview: Reading FC v Sheffield Wednesday|url=https://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/charles-watts-big-match-preview-6683750|publisher=Get Reading|date=7 February 2014|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref> By March, Leigterwood returned to training.<ref>{{cite news|title=Injured Reading FC stars on the way back|url=https://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/injured-reading-fc-stars-way-6858563|publisher=Get Reading|date=21 March 2014|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref> After a year out injured, Leigertwood made his Reading return on 8 April 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bournemouth 3-1 Reading|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?MatchId=3632983&tcmuri=921713|publisher=Reading FC|accessdate=9 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413142056/http://www.readingfc.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?MatchId=3632983&tcmuri=921713|archivedate=24 August 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the follow\u2013up match, however, he came on as a substitute for [[Danny Williams (soccer, born 1989)|Danny Williams]] in the 61st minutes, but was sent\u2013off for a second bookable offence, in a 1\u20131 draw against Leicester City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reading FC 1, Leicester City FC 1: Royals edge back into the play-offs|url=http://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/reading-fc-1-leicester-city-6989144|publisher=Get Reading|date=14 April 2014|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref> After missing out two matches, Leigertwood went on to play the last two matches for the side.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2014/april/midfielder-back-from-ban/|title=Midfielder back from ban|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=22 April 2014|accessdate=24 August 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824133850/https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2014/april/midfielder-back-from-ban/|archivedate=24 August 2019|url-status=live}}<br>{{cite news|title=Reading FC 2, Burnley FC 2: Last gasp heartbreak as Royals miss out on the play-offs|url=https://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/reading-fc-2-burnley-fc-7069222|publisher=Get Reading|date=3 May 2014|accessdate=24 August 2019}}<br>{{cite news|title=Doncaster Rovers FC 1, Reading FC 3: Pogrebnyak the hero for Royals|url=https://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/doncaster-rovers-fc-1-reading-703746|publisher=Get Reading|date=26 April 2014|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref> At the end of the 2013\u201314 season, Leigertwood went on to make four appearances for the side.\n\nOn 6 May 2014, Leigertwood was released from Reading, along with five players.<ref name=\"5 released\">{{cite web|title=Jobi, Mikele & Kaspars to move on|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/mcanuff-leigertwood-gorkss-leave-060514-1539505.aspx|publisher=Reading FC|accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref> and in July joined [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on trial.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mikele Leigertwood has chance to earn Nottingham Forest contract|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Mikele-Leigertwood-chance-earn-Nottingham-Forest/story-21460176-detail/story.html|website=nottinghampost.com|publisher=[[Nottingham Post]]|accessdate=14 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715004737/http://www.nottinghampost.com/Mikele-Leigertwood-chance-earn-Nottingham-Forest/story-21460176-detail/story.html|archivedate=15 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Whilst on trial, Leigertwood sustained a hip injury which forced him to retire from the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28640288|title=Nottingham Forest: Leigertwood's fitness key to possible deal|work=BBC Sport|date=4 August 2014|accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref> His official retirement wasn't confirmed until the following year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leigertwood makes a start at Lions|url=https://www.londonlions.com/leigertwood-sees-lions-as-a-great-start/|website=londonlions.com|publisher=[[London Lions F.C.]]|date=20 July 2015|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Post\u2013Playing Career==\nAfter retiring from professional football, Leigertwood took up a coaching role at [[London Lions F.C.|Maccabi London Lions]] as their Sunday Team Coach.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leigertwood makes a start at Lions|url=http://www.londonlions.com/leigertwood-sees-lions-as-a-great-start/|website=londonlions.com|publisher=[[London Lions F.C.]]|accessdate=11 November 2015|date=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 July 2016 Leigertwood returned to [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] as Academy Loan Manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2016/july/welcome-back-ledge/|title=Welcome back Ledge!|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=19 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212084739/https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2016/july/welcome-back-ledge/|archivedate=24 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nLeigertwood is eligible to represent [[Antigua and Barbuda national football team|Antigua and Barbuda]]. [[Willie Donachie]], Antigua and Barbuda's manager, tried to get Leigertwood into the squad for a World Cup Qualifier in June 2008, but Leigertwood had a wedding to attend.<ref>{{cite news|title=Willie Donachie attempts success with Antigua|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2301893/Willie-Donachie-attempts-success-with-Antigua.html|publisher=Telegraph|date=30 September 2008|accessdate=5 November 2008|location=London|first=Mark|last=Armstrong}}</ref> He's also eligible to represent [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines national football team|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]].<ref>{{cite news|title=CALYPSO TEAM IN WORLD CUP RUNNING|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/calypso-team-in-world-cup-running-1600400|publisher=Daily Mirror|date=11 July 2004|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhile serving a four match ban after receiving a red card  in a match against Birmingham City on 28 October 2008, he accepted a call up for the [[2008 Caribbean Championship]] to represent Antigua and Barbuda.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} He made his national debut on 5 November 2008 in a 3\u20132 loss against [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]] and scored his first goal in their next match against [[Guyana national football team|Guyana]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} In November 2010, he returned to the national team and participated in the second stage of the [[2010 Caribbean Championship]], playing in all three matches.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kyle Walker injury adds to QPR selection dilemmas|url=https://www.mylondon.news/sport/other-sport/kyle-walker-injury-adds-qpr-599209|publisher=My London News|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 3 May 2014.}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League{{ref label|League|A|}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other{{ref label|Other|B|}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!